/about_set.html\" target\u003d\"_blank\"\u003eWeikersheim Observatory\u003c/a\u003e in southern Germany, the picture is a single exposure adjusted to reduce the difference in brightness between Saturn and the cratered lunar surface.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","pubDate":"2013-Apr-07","imgURL":"http://24.media.tumblr.com/eb79629afafd36f86de49b8f876b4037/tumblr_mkvuxuvIHb1qdvdz5o1_75sq.jpg","source":""},{"artcileUrl":"http://phys.org/news/2013-04-star-birth-cepheus.html","description":"\u003cp\u003eWatching a celestial nursery - \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e\u0026#8220;Much like archeologists who reconstruct ancient cities from shards of debris strewn over time, astronomers must reconstruct the birth process of stars indirectly, by observing stars in different stages of the process and inferring the changes that take place. Studies show that half of the common stars, including our Sun, formed in massive clusters, rich with young stars, from which they eventually escape.\u0026#8221;\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e","pubDate":"2013-Apr-04","imgURL":"http://24.media.tumblr.com/30b8a7bdf61f9a01767bd6901846097a/tumblr_mknmq1wDDf1s52209o1_75sq.jpg","source":""}]